paragraphs.title: Processing
paragraphs.text:
%md

All of that is great, but it's really better if the data can be processed. You can do whatever data manipulations you need in another language, but why not set up a DeepSee cube that will handle things like combining multiple tables, encoding strings into integers, and just generally gathering together data in a machine-learning-friendly form?

paragraphs.title: Partial One-Hot-Encoding
paragraphs.text:
%md

It's a good step in the right direction. Com and CurCom are diagnoses (comorbidities and current comorbidities, or what you've been diagnosed with before and what you're in the hospital for right now.) That said, both of those are actually lists; somebody could easily have both chronic pulmonary disease (5) and mild liver disease (10), making their Com column equal to "5,10". To properly deal with that, we one-hot-encode those columns. We use a stored procedure we call an Analytical Base Table (ABT).

paragraphs.title: Full One-Hot-Encoding and Normalization
paragraphs.text:
%md
That's what you need for many tree-based algorithms (random forests, etc. in Spark, for example). Plenty of other algorithms need a little more processing, though. We can do that in an ABT, too!
